BG, HSBC, Sainsbury, National Grid: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 
2011-05-11T06:46:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/firstgroup-sainsbury-national-grid-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  Futures on the benchmark FTSE 100 Index increased 0.4
percent to 6,016 at 7:45 a.m. in  London . The FTSE 100 gained
76.2, or 1.3 percent, to 6,018.89 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share
Index also advanced 1.3 percent to 3,133.73, while Ireland’s
ISEQ Index climbed 1.1 percent to 3,005.43.  BG Group Plc (BG/)  : The U.K.’s third-largest natural gas
producer said it plans to drill more wells off the coast of
Tanzania to find sufficient reserves to underpin the development
of a two-unit land-based plant to liquefy the fuel. The shares
fell 1.6 percent to 1,412.5 pence.  FirstGroup Plc (FGP)  : The U.K. train operator said full-
year profit before tax from continuing operations fell to 127.2
million pounds ($208.2 million) from 175.3 million pounds a year
earlier. The stock rose 1.6 percent to 344.2 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  :  Europe ’s biggest bank by
market value said it will target cost cuts of $2.5 billion to
$3.5 billion by 2013 and prepare for stricter capital rules. The
shares advanced 1.2 percent to 656.2 pence.  J Sainsbury Plc (SBRY)  : The U.K.’s third-largest
supermarket owner reported full-year underlying pretax profit of
665 million pounds. Analysts had estimated profit on that basis
of 656.7 million pounds. The shares increased 1.9 percent to
355.8 pence.  Kerry Group Plc (KYG)  : Ireland’s largest food company’s
biggest shareholder, Kerry Co-operative Creameries Ltd., sold
1.5 million shares, cutting its stake to 22.8 percent, a
spokesman for the company said. The stock gained 0.4 percent to
28.94 euros.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc (LSE)  : The merger of the
London Stock Exchange Group Plc and TMX Group Inc. “will go
through,” Thomas A. Kloet, TMX’s chief executive officer, said.
Separately, The LSE’s calendar of initial public offerings is
“pretty full” and the London exchange predicts that “dozens”
of company will list in the coming months, the Financial Times
reported, citing LSE Chief Executive Officer  Xavier Rolet .  The stock advanced 0.2 percent to 827.5 pence.  National Grid Plc (NG/)  : The power network manager for
the U.K. extended work on its 2,000-megawatt link that connects
Britain and France. The shares jumped 2.4 percent to 629.5
pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
